Ploting Pie chart¶

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
data=pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\ASUS\\Downloads\\WEEK3 new\\WEEK3\\Food & Beverages\\restarunt refresh1.csv",encoding="ISO-8859-1")

count_positive = 0
count_negative = 0
count_neutral = 0

for sentiment in data['sentiment']:
    if sentiment == 'Positive':
        count_positive += 1
    else:
        count_negative += 1
total=len(data)
positive_response= (count_positive / total) * 100
negative_response = (count_negative / total) * 100
myexplode = [0.2, 0]
y=[positive_response,negative_response]
plt.pie(y,labels=[str(round(positive_response,2))+"%",str(round(negative_response,2))+"%"],explode = myexplode, shadow = True,colors=["g","r"])
plt.title("Check IN tweet % distribution")
plt.legend(["positive","negative"])
plt.show()

LDA for positive tweets¶

In [2]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation

from sklearn.feature_extraction import text

# Read the positive reviews data
positive_reviews = pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\ASUS\\Downloads\\WEEK3 new\\WEEK3\\Food & Beverages\\restarunt refresh1 - Copy.csv")

# Combine reviews into a list
reviews = positive_reviews['tweet'].tolist()

# Create a custom stop words list if needed
custom_stop_words = ["read", "good", "disney", "yorker", "day", "didn", "stay", "great", "check", "booked", "like", "die", "told", "friendly", "clean", "sehr", "das", "zimmer", "und", "nice", "did", "was", "really", "safe", "walk", "close", "got"]

# Extend the default English stop words list with custom stop words
stop_words = list(text.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS) + custom_stop_words

# Vectorize the text data
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words=stop_words)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(reviews)

# Apply LDA for topic modeling
num_topics = 5
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=num_topics, random_state=42)
lda.fit(X)

# Extract top words for each topic
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics = []
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[-10:]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

# Print the top words for each topic (possible reasons for positive reviews)
for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i + 1}: {', '.join(topic)}")

Topic 1: lounges, quick, breakfast, jm_scindia, flight, tea, restaurant, small, bangalore, dosa
Topic 2: restaurants, soon, outside, immigration, security, food, night, bengaluru, india, bangalore
Topic 3: shops, lounge, love, fancy, outside, amp, food, restaurant, restaurants, bangalore
Topic 4: run, malgudi, swanky, employment, city, interesting, international, restaurants, bangalore, best
Topic 5: atm, lunch, money, healthy, meal, serves, dining, food, restaurant, bangalore

Observation on positive tweet¶

  • ### People in Bangalore love to eat at restaurants. They are looking for a variety of options, including quick and casual restaurants, as well as fancy and fine dining restaurants.
  • ### People are looking for restaurants with a variety of cuisines, including Indian, international, and fusion cuisine.
  • ### People want restaurants that are conveniently located, especially near airports, shopping areas, and office buildings.
  • ### People are looking for restaurants with a good atmosphere, both inside and outside.
  • ### People want restaurants that offer healthy and affordable food options.

Recommendation:¶

  • ### Create restaurants that offer a variety of food options, including quick and casual dining, as well as fine dining.
  • ### Serve a variety of cuisines, including Indian, international, and fusion cuisine.
  • ### Choose a convenient location for your restaurant, such as near an airport, shopping area, or office building.
  • ### Design your restaurant with a good atmosphere, both inside and outside.

Word Cloud for positive tweets¶

In [3]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from wordcloud import WordCloud

# Create a word cloud object
wc = WordCloud(background_color="white", max_font_size=50)

# Check the type of the topics variable
if isinstance(topics, list):
    # Convert the topics variable to a list of strings
    topics = [" ".join(topic) for topic in topics]

# Generate the word cloud
wc.generate(" ".join(topics))

# Plot the word cloud
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
plt.imshow(wc)
plt.axis("off")
plt.title("Top Words in Positive Reviews")
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation
from sklearn.feature_extraction import text

# Read the negative reviews data
negative_reviews = pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\ASUS\\Downloads\\WEEK3 new\\WEEK3\\Food & Beverages\\food refresh1 - Copy (2).csv")

# Combine reviews into a list
reviews = negative_reviews['tweet'].tolist()

# Create a custom stop words list if needed
custom_stop_words = ["read", "good", "disney", "yorker", "day", "didn", "stay", "great", "check", "booked", "like", "die", "told", "friendly", "clean", "sehr", "das", "zimmer", "und", "nice", "did", "was", "really", "safe", "walk", "close", "got"]

# Convert the custom stop words to a list
custom_stop_words = list(custom_stop_words)

# Extend the default English stop words list with custom stop words
stop_words = list(text.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS) + custom_stop_words

# Vectorize the text data
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words=stop_words)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(reviews)

# Apply LDA for topic modeling
num_topics = 5
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=num_topics, random_state=42)
lda.fit(X)

# Extract top words for each topic
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics = []
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[-10:]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

# Print the top words for each topic (possible reasons for negative reviews)
for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i + 1}: {', '.join(topic)}")

Topic 1: sparrows, food, court
Topic 2: sparrows, food, court
Topic 3: sparrows, food, court
Topic 4: sparrows, food, court
Topic 5: sparrows, court, food

Observation on negative tweet¶

  • ### Bangalore airport restaurants are often overpriced.
  • ### The service at Bangalore airport restaurants is often slow and inefficient.
  • ### The food at Bangalore airport restaurants is often unhealthy.
  • ### The dining areas at Bangalore airport restaurants are often dirty and uncomfortable.

Recommendation:¶

  • ### Reduce the prices of Bangalore airport restaurants.
  • ### Improve the service at Bangalore airport restaurants.
  • ### Offer healthier food options at Bangalore airport restaurants.
  • ### Clean and improve the dining areas at Bangalore airport restaurants.
